10: But, Sir Alk! We have only just begun!
13:
Heh. Bruises here, ouches there, and
wounds everywhere... I'm done for.
16:
My, my. Aren't you the poet. But you
shall have to stand sooner or later.
18: No... I'm going to lie here forever.
22:
I suppose I'll have to offer you a small
incentive then.
30:
You have five duels to lay one hit on
me, Sir Alk. Do so, and I'll pronounce
you the victor.
32:
However, the loser must do whatever
the winner says. Are we agreed?
36:
Wh-whatever the winner says?
That's a lot to ask for...
41:
Then one hit among ten duels?
Or a hundred?
45:
Okay, now that kind of hurts.
I can DEFINITELY land a blow if you
fight me that many times.
50: Perfect! Let our hundred duels begin!
55: Whoa! Hold on! I haven't agreed to—
59: Yes, but I won't take no for an answer!
64:
Mmm! Sir Alk! This Mont Blanc is
delicious—all the more so thanks to the
blackcurrant sauce!
68:
Why did I go through with this?
My body didn't hold out anywhere
CLOSE to a hundred duels.
71:
Still, the thirteen matches we DID
complete were superb!
75:
But is this really enough? The bet was
to do anything the winner asked for.
All I've done is treat you to cake.
80:
Hehehe. Would you have preferred
a more elaborate request?
87:
The Farlands are building up their
military?
89:
Yep. And the head of the Tris family is
to be appointed governor-general.
Of course, his eldest son will manage
state affairs.
91:
You think war's on the horizon?
Not that it'll affect us either way.
93:
It could, if they start recruiting mercs.
Though we're better suited to exploring
dungeons and such.
97: Tris? In the Farlands? Isn't that—
101: Yes. They speak of my homeland.
103:
And the eldest son they mentioned?
That would be my big brother.
106: Huh?! Does that make you a princess?
110:
No. Princes and princesses come from
the royal family of Nialas.
112:
The Tris are merely one of the
Nine Noble Houses. A clan of warriors,
if you will.
116:
Oooh, warriors, huh? Does that mean
your brother is strong too?
121:
Indeed. I was unable to beat him until
the age of twelve—the only person
I had never defeated, actually!
123:
Though, I wouldn't know how we stack
up these days. I have been prohibited
from dueling with the knightly class.
130:
Well, according to Father, falling to my
skill would rob a knight of their honor.
132:
But I can think of two who lose no
honor, despite their myriad losses: the
youngest son of the Nouin family...
and you, Sir Alk.
136:
Uh, I hope you mean that as
a compliment...
139: Tenacity is a rare gift! Feel proud!
142: But, I admit, one thing still intrigues me...
144:
You don't find it shameful to lose to
an unknighted woman?
150:
But I've met tons of strong people,
from all different backgrounds.
Take Stella, for instance.
153:
Lady Stella? Ah, you're referring to more
than battle acumen, aren't you?
158:
Yeah. Everyone around here is good at
something in their own way—they keep
me on my toes.
160:
Thinking back on my journey, I realize
THEY'RE the ones who made it possible.
Couldn't imagine life without them now.
163:
Your companions truly mean
a lot to you...
167:
Yeah. And training with you is just as
enjoyable, Celtie.
171:
And I like sneaking out to eat cake
together even more!
175:
It's fun having someone like a little
sister—even if she can clean my clock!
181:
My, even you can catch people off
guard at times!
188:
Never you mind. How about we make it
a tradition to come and eat cake after
every duel?
192:
Really? EVERY time? You sure?
We'll balloon like crazy, though...
196:
Sigh... Sir Alk... You've gone and
spoiled everything.
200: Argh, whatever! Thanks for the cake!
204:
Oh, and don't forget! Our bet still
stands! You must manage to hit me
once within a hundred duels.
208:
Or you shall have to follow my every
whim!
213: Wait, so this cake was a lie?!
